04899nam a2200673Ia 9780801456169DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1080549872  a(OCoLC)984682761  a97808014561697 a10.7591/97808014561692doi  a(DE-B1597)481759  a(OCoLC)908550533  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aQL458.42.L6 7aNAT0170002bisacsh04a595.4/42231 aVetter, Richard S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Brown Recluse Spider /cRichard S. Vetter. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (200 p.) :bFull color throughout, 49 photographs, 6 line figures, 6 tables, 5 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Taxonomy -- t2. Identification -- t3. Misidentification -- t4. Life History and Biology -- t5. Distribution -- t6. Medical Aspects -- t7. Medical Misdiagnoses -- t8. Human Psychology and the Brown Recluse Spider -- t9. Bites and Alleged Bites by Other Spiders -- t10. Control Measures -- tGlossary -- tReferences and Further Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe brown recluse is a fascinating spider very well adapted to dwelling in houses and other buildings. Because of this very quality and the ghastly reputation associated with the medical consequences of its bite, it has become infamous throughout North America. Although recluse spiders can cause serious skin injuries and, in very rare cases, death, the danger posed by this spider is often exaggerated as a result of arachnophobia and the misdiagnosis of non-spider-related conditions as brown recluse bites. These misdiagnoses often occur in areas of North America where the spider does not exist, making legitimate bites improbable. One of the greatest factors that keeps the myths alive is misidentification of common (and harmless) spiders as brown recluses. With this book, Richard S. Vetter hopes to educate readers regarding the biology of the spider and medical aspects of its bites, to reduce the incidence of misdiagnoses, and to quell misplaced anxiety. In The Brown Recluse Spider, Vetter covers topics such as taxonomy, identification, misidentification, life history characteristics and biology, medical aspects of envenomations, medical conditions misdiagnosed as brown recluse bites, other spider species of medical consideration (several of which have been wrongly implicated as threats to human health), and the psychology behind the entrenched reasons why people believe so deeply in the presence of the spider in the face of strong, contradictory information. Vetter also makes recommendations for control of the spider for households in areas where the spiders are found and describes other species of recluse spiders in North America. Although The Brown Recluse Spider was written for a general audience, it is also a valuable source of information for arachnologists and medical personnel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBrown recluse spiderxVenomxToxicology. 0aBrown recluse spiderzUnited StatesxGeographical distribution. 0aBrown recluse spider. 4aEntomology. 4aGeneral Science. 4aNature Guides & Natural History. 7aNATURE / Animals / Insects & Spiders.2bisacsh  aZoology, arachnids, arachnophobia, spider-related conditions, misinformation, taxonomy, animal identification, animal control.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145616940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801456169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97808